# Copy this to .env and fill in values. Never commit .env.

# App
APP_ENV=development
SECRET_KEY=change-me-to-a-long-random-string

# Database
DATABASE_URL=postgresql+asyncpg://pantrychef:pantrychef@localhost:5433/pantrychef

# Redis
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379/0

# OpenAI
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...

# AWS SES
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
AWS_REGION=us-east-1
SES_SENDER_EMAIL=noreply@yourdomain.com
```

> **Why `.env.example` and not `.env`?** `.env` holds secrets — it must never be committed. `.env.example` is the contract that tells a new developer what variables they need. This is standard practice on every real team.

---

### `.gitignore`
```
.env
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.pytest_cache/
.ruff_cache/
dist/
*.egg-info/